                                 FINAL REPORT
 CT OF THE ABDOMEN AND PELVIS WITHOUT IV CONTRAST [**2107-11-2**].

 HISTORY:  Status post cardiac catheterization, now with severe back pain.
 Assess for a retroperitoneal bleed.

 TECHNIQUE:  Helically-acquired contiguous axial images were obtained from the
 lung bases to the pubic symphysis without the administration of IV contrast.

 CT OF ABDOMEN WITHOUT IV CONTRAST:  The lung bases show bibasilar atelectasis
 with a probable calcified granuloma within the posterior right lung base. Also
 noted are multiple cardiac stents.  The liver, gallbladder, spleen, pancreas,
 adrenal glands, and visualized loops of large/small bowel are normal.  Noted
 is mild calcification of the distal abdominal aorta and proximal iliac
 arteries. There is a small amount of residual contrast within the proximal
 renal collecting systems.  The kidneys are otherwise normal in appearance.
 There is no retroperitoneal fluid collection seen.  The visualized soft
 tissues and subcutaneous regions are normal.

 CT OF PELVIS WITHOUT IV CONTRAST:  Residual IV contrast  is seen within a
 well-distended urinary bladder. The prostate, rectum, and unopacified loops of
 bowel are normal.  There are no abnormal fluid collections within the
 visualized pelvis or soft tissues. Noted is some soft- tissue stranding in the
 region of the right groin, consistent with the patient's stated history of a
 recent cardiac catheterization.  There is also the suggestion of a fat-
 containing right inguinal hernia and a possible right-sided hydrocele.

 The visualized osseous structures are unremarkable.

 IMPRESSION:
 1) No evidence of a retroperitoneal bleed.
 2) Mild calcification of the distal aorta and proximal iliac arteries, as
 described above.
 3) Probable fat-containing right inguinal hernia.

 The findings were discussed with the house staff caring for the patient at the
 time of the examination.

 FEVER, UNKNOWN ORIGIN (FUO, HYPERTHERMIA, PYREXIA)
 HYPOPHOSPHATEMIA (LOW PHOSPHATE)
   24 year old man with a history of episodic dizziness, h/o pneumothorax
   who was admitted for fever and hypotension with good response to fluid
   resuscitation but persistently elevated temperature and findings on
   CXR.
    1) FEVER, TACHYCARDIA, AND HYPOTENSION. Met SIRS criteria for fever
   and tachycardia. Since admission, T up to 101.2,  not tachycardic, SBPs
   down to 77 but generally in 110s.  Persistent sore throat, rhinorrhea,
   headache, and nausea, with continued patchy opacities on CXR. Although
   viral infection/ influenza is the most likely cause, the differential
   diagnosis continues to be bacterial pneumonia and viral meningitis.
   Currently treated empirically for community-acquired PNA (ceftriaxone
   and azithromycin), with ceftriaxone dosed for meningitis coverage. If
   isolation of [**Doctor Last Name **] in sputum or if flu swab is positive, can de-escalte
   ceftriaxone from meningitis dosing. If fevers continue to spike and
   alternate source is not identified, revisit option of LP with the
   patient and continue empiric treatment for meningitis.
   -Repeat CXR this afternoon.
   -Continue azithromycin and cetriaxone (day 1 and 2 of 7, respectively)
   for community-acquired PNA
   -Acetaminophen for T>38F.
   -Follow up blood cultures, urine culture, sputum sample, and flu swab.
   2.) HYPOTENSION. SBP generally 110s since admission following 5 L IVF.
   The differential diagnosis includes vasodilation in association with
   SIRS +/- volume depletion. No signs of acute blood loss; Hct likely low
   due to hemodilution (WBC and platelets also low). At this point, his BP
